==Development==
[[File:Raoul Barbet & Michel Koch on Life Is Strange.webm|thumb|right|alt=Gameplay video|250px|Barbet and Koch describe the game and discuss the role of protagonist Max Caulfield.]]
''Life Is Strange'' was [[Dontnod Entertainment]]'s second title with a female protagonist. Dontnod published a developer diary that said most prospective publishers were unwilling to publish a game unless it had a male protagonist.<ref name="square1">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/other-publishers-told-us-to-make-it-a-male-lead-ch/1100-6424577/ |title="Other Publishers Told Us to Make It a Male Lead Character," Life is Strange Dev Says |first=Emanuel |last=Maiberg |date=10 January 2015 |work=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=21 July 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719152644/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/other-publishers-told-us-to-make-it-a-male-lead-ch/1100-6424577/ |archivedate=19 July 2015  }}</ref><ref name="square2">{{cite web|url=http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/139401-Publishers-Disliked-Dontnods-Life-is-Strange-Having-Female-Leads|title=Publishers Wanted Life is Strange Devs to Make Leads Male|first=Sarah|last=LeBoeuf|date=11 January 2015|work=[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]|accessdate=12 January 2015|archivedate=6 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206164909/http://www.escapistmagazine.com/news/view/139401-Publishers-Disliked-Dontnods-Life-is-Strange-Having-Female-Leads|deadurl=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Most publishers had the same objection to Dontnod's first project, ''[[Remember Me (video game)|Remember Me]]''.<ref name="first">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/publishers-said-you-cant-have-a-female-character-says-remember-me-dev/1100-6405550/|title=Publishers said 'You can't have a female character,' says Remember Me dev|first=Eddie|last=Makuch|date=19 March 2013|work=[[GameSpot]]|accessdate=12 November 2014|archivedate=29 December 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131229210302/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/publishers-said-you-cant-have-a-female-character-says-remember-me-dev/1100-6405550/|deadurl=no}}</ref> Dontnod CEO Oskar Guilbert also challenged the idea at the start.<ref name="3dg3">{{cite magazine|title=Edge #293|first=Ben|last=Barnes|magazine=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]]|location=p. 94-97|publisher=[[Future plc]]|date=June 2016}}</ref> [[Square Enix]] was the only publisher with no intention to change the female protagonist.<ref name="hip to be square">{{cite web|url=http://kotaku.com/publishers-wanted-to-change-life-is-stranges-protagonis-1678811522 |title=Publishers Wanted To Change Life Is Strange's Protagonists Into Men |first=Mike |last=Rougeau |date=11 January 2015 |work=[[Kotaku]] |accessdate=31 October 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151117104746/http://kotaku.com/publishers-wanted-to-change-life-is-stranges-protagonis-1678811522 |archivedate=17 November 2015  }}</ref> Dontnod co-founder Jean-Maxime Moris said [[gender equality]] in video games was "a great debate to have",<ref name="50%" /> but "we're not pretending to address the issue or use the issue to stand out from the rest".<ref name="characters">{{cite web|url=http://thegamefanatics.com/2014/10/12/life-strange-brief-yet-delightful-look-next-game-behind-developers-remember|title=Life is Strange A Brief yet Delightful Look at the Next Game Behind the Developers of Remember Me|first=Carlos|last=Ovalle|date=12 October 2014|work=The Game Fanatics|accessdate=12 November 2014|archivedate=12 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112072937/http://thegamefanatics.com/2014/10/12/life-strange-brief-yet-delightful-look-next-game-behind-developers-remember|deadurl=no}}</ref>

Development of ''Life Is Strange'' began in April 2013 with a team of 15, and more people were added when the collaboration with Square Enix began.<ref name="development">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/videos/life-is-strange-developer-diary-a-new-beginning/2300-6422919/ |title=Life is Strange – Developer Diary: A New Beginning |first=Gajan |last=Kulasingham |date=9 January 2015 |work=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=21 July 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209052241/http://www.gamespot.com/videos/life-is-strange-developer-diary-a-new-beginning/2300-6422919/ |archivedate=9 February 2015  }}</ref><ref name="team">{{cite web|url=http://www.momenta.online/2016/02/edouard-caplain-on-the-art-behind-life-is-strange/|title=Edouard Caplain on the Art Behind Life Is Strange|date=9 February 2016|work=Momenta|accessdate=18 February 2016|archivedate=27 July 2016|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160727023538/http://www.momenta.online/2016/02/edouard-caplain-on-the-art-behind-life-is-strange/|deadurl=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref>  Dontnod told Square Enix about ''Life Is Strange'' only after Square Enix turned down a [[Sales presentation|pitch]] for a larger game.<ref name="solicited success" /><ref name="pitch on">{{cite web|url=http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/they-originally-pitched-a-different-game-how-square-enix-discovered-life-is-strange/0153982 |title='They originally pitched a different game': how Square Enix discovered Life Is Strange |first=Christopher |last=Dring |date=7 August 2015 |work=[[Market for Home Computing and Video Games|MCV]] |accessdate=31 March 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506210100/http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/they-originally-pitched-a-different-game-how-square-enix-discovered-life-is-strange/0153982 |archivedate=6 May 2016  }}</ref> Before signing with Square Enix, ''Life Is Strange'' was imagined as a full-length video game that Dontnod would self-publish. However, the publisher surmised that it would be more successful as an episodic title.<ref name="3dg3" /> The game was originally codenamed ''What If'' but then retitled to distinguish itself from the [[The F Word (2013 film)|film of the same name]].<ref name="what if">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/square-enix-s-life-is-strange-considered-100-diffe/1100-6425742/ |title=Square Enix's Life is Strange Considered 100 Different Names |first=Eddie |last=Makuch |date=6 March 2015 |work=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=7 March 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150307215843/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/square-enix-s-life-is-strange-considered-100-diffe/1100-6425742/ |archivedate=7 March 2015  }}</ref> ''Life Is Strange'' was born of the idea for the rewind mechanic, which the developer had already experimented on with their last game ''Remember Me''. The lead character Max was created with the ability to rewind time to supplement this mechanism.<ref name="birth">{{cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2015/5/19/8612335/life-is-strange-making-of |title=How adventure game Life is Strange blends time travel and teen drama |first=Andrew |last=Webster |date=19 May 2015 |work=[[The Verge]] |accessdate=19 May 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150520104539/http://www.theverge.com/2015/5/19/8612335/life-is-strange-making-of |archivedate=20 May 2015  }}</ref> The episodic format was decided upon by the studio for creative reasons, financial restrictions<ref name="format">{{cite web|url=http://www.usgamer.net/articles/life-is-stranges-triforce-of-influences|title=Life is Strange's "Triforce" of Influences|first=Kat|last=Bailey|date=31 January 2015|work=[[Eurogamer#Subsidiaries|USgamer]]|accessdate=1 February 2015|archivedate=2 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150202123538/http://www.usgamer.net/articles/life-is-stranges-triforce-of-influences|deadurl=no}}</ref> and [[marketing]] purposes,<ref name="aggregated" /> allowing them to tell the story in its preferred slow pace.<ref name="slow pace">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/apr/26/life-is-strange-episodic-video-game-dontnod |title=Life Is Strange: episodic video games prove as addictive as episodic TV |first=Calum |last=Marsh |date=26 April 2015 |work=[[The Guardian]] |accessdate=26 April 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518090434/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2015/apr/26/life-is-strange-episodic-video-game-dontnod |archivedate=18 May 2015  }}</ref> The [[Pacific Northwest]] was picked as the setting for the purpose of conveying a [[Nostalgia|nostalgic]] and autumnal feel to the game.<ref name="setting">{{cite web|url=http://gamerhub.tv/videos/life-is-strange-gameplay-preview-interview/2014/08/27/|title=Life Is Strange Gameplay Preview Interview|date=27 August 2014|work=GamerHub|accessdate=11 November 2014|archivedate=12 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112032016/http://gamerhub.tv/videos/life-is-strange-gameplay-preview-interview/2014/08/27/|deadurl=no}}</ref> The development team visited the region,<ref name="shortlong" /> took photographs, looked at local newspapers and used [[Google Street View]] to make sure the environment was accurately portrayed.<ref name="archetypes" /><ref name="googlestreetview">{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2015/01/29/life-is-strange-pc-ps4-xbox-one-video/|title=Final Life is Strange developer diary focuses on music, voice actors|first=Stephany|last=Nunneley|date=29 January 2015|work=[[VG247]]|accessdate=29 January 2015|archivedate=29 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150129233119/http://www.vg247.com/2015/01/29/life-is-strange-pc-ps4-xbox-one-video/|deadurl=no}}</ref>

It was decided early on that most of the budget be spent on the writing and voice actors.<ref name="release schedule 1">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-03-18-publishers-wanted-life-is-stranges-main-character-to-be-a-guy-qtes-added|title=Life is Strange dev talks lip-syncing, release schedule and publisher demands|first=Tom|last=Phillips|date=18 March 2015|work=[[Eurogamer]]|accessdate=18 March 2015|archivedate=18 March 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318133732/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2015-03-18-publishers-wanted-life-is-stranges-main-character-to-be-a-guy-qtes-added|deadurl=no}}</ref> The original story was written in French by Jean-Luc Cano, and converted into a game script by the co-directors and design team. It was subsequently handed over to Christian Divine and Cano to be fine tuned in English.<ref name="script process">{{cite web|url=http://www.redbull.com/en/games/stories/1331743857254/life-is-strange-interview |title=Be kind, rewind: The making of Life Is Strange |first=Damien |last=McFerran |date=28 August 2015 |work=[[Red Bull|Red Bull Games]] |accessdate=30 August 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150831002923/http://www.redbull.com/en/games/stories/1331743857254/life-is-strange-interview |archivedate=31 August 2015  }}</ref><ref name="cano">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-04-09-life-is-strange |title=Life is Strange team talk fan theories, that season finale and more |first=Tom |last=Phillips |date=18 April 2016 |work=[[Eurogamer]] |accessdate=20 April 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160420131057/http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2016-04-09-life-is-strange |archivedate=20 April 2016  }}</ref> Story and [[Character arc|character development]] were highlighted over [[Graphic adventure game#Point-and-click adventure|point-and-click]] puzzles,<ref name="highlighting">{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2015/01/13/life-is-strange-is-for-telltale_heavy-rain-fans/|title=Life is Strange: "this is definitely a game for the Telltale and Heavy Rain fans"|first=Brenna|last=Hillier|date=13 January 2015|work=[[VG247]]|accessdate=20 July 2015|archivedate=13 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150113184014/http://www.vg247.com/2015/01/13/life-is-strange-is-for-telltale_heavy-rain-fans/|deadurl=no}}</ref> making choice and consequence integral to how the narrative unfolds.<ref name="choice">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2014/8/11/5990851/life-is-strange-dontnod-entertainment-ps4-ps3-xbox-one-360-pc|title=Life is Strange, episodic adventure game, coming from Remember Me dev|first=Samit|last=Sarkar|date=11 August 2014|work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]|accessdate=11 November 2014|archivedate=6 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206232452/http://www.polygon.com/2014/8/11/5990851/life-is-strange-dontnod-entertainment-ps4-ps3-xbox-one-360-pc|deadurl=no}}</ref> Hannah Telle auditioned for Max Caulfield in July 2014 and was offered the part; [[Ashly Burch]] auditioned for both Max and her given role Chloe Price. The recording sessions were done in [[Los Angeles]], California, with the French developer brought in via [[Skype]].<ref name="audition 1">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/09/12/hannah-telle-involvement-in-life-is-strange-is-the-greatest-honor-2/166374/ |title=Hannah Telle: Involvement in Life Is Strange is the 'Greatest Honor' |first=Adnan |last=Riaz |date=12 September 2015 |work=[[Hardcore Gamer]] |accessdate=22 November 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119063952/http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/09/12/hannah-telle-involvement-in-life-is-strange-is-the-greatest-honor-2/166374/ |archivedate=19 November 2015  }}</ref><ref name="audition 2">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/videos/life-is-strange-episodic-heartstrings-kinda-funny-/2300-6425679/ |title=Life Is Strange: Episodic Heartstrings – Kinda Funny at E3 2015 |first=Jeremy |last=Jayne |date=18 June 2015 |work=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=22 November 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151103172236/http://www.gamespot.com/videos/life-is-strange-episodic-heartstrings-kinda-funny-/2300-6425679/ |archivedate=3 November 2015  }}</ref>

[[File:Life Is Strange.gif|thumb|left|Key art for episode five from rough concept to final version.]]

Although it holds significant differences from ''Remember Me'', the game addresses similar themes of [[memory]] and [[Identity (philosophy)|identity]].<ref name="memoryidentity">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/08/13/gamescom-2014-how-life-is-strange-gets-female-protagonists-right|title=Gamescom 2014: How 'Life is Strange' Gets Female Protagonists Right|first=Brian|last=Albert|date=13 August 2014|work=[[IGN]]|accessdate=11 November 2014|archivedate=12 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112052448/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/08/13/gamescom-2014-how-life-is-strange-gets-female-protagonists-right|deadurl=no}}</ref> ''Life Is Strange'' was specified as an [[Analog device|analogue]] look at human identity in contrast to ''Remember Me'', the [[Digital media|digital]] view of the same theme.<ref name="analogue">{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-feature/2015/01/28/feature-life-is-strange-interview-and-hands-on-impressions|title=FEATURE: "Life is Strange" Interview and Hands-on Impressions|first=Nate|last=Ming|date=29 January 2015|work=[[Crunchyroll]]|accessdate=29 January 2015|archivedate=29 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150129193102/http://www.crunchyroll.com/anime-feature/2015/01/28/feature-life-is-strange-interview-and-hands-on-impressions|deadurl=no}}</ref> Running on an improved version of [[Unreal Engine#Unreal Engine 3|Unreal Engine 3]], it makes use of the tools and special effects like [[High-dynamic-range rendering|lighting]] and [[depth of field]] engineered for ''Remember Me'' as well as subsequent advances.<ref name="characters" /><ref name="format" /> Visual effects like [[Image editing|post-processes]], [[Multiple exposure|double exposure]] and overlapping [[particle system|screen space particles]] were used as an artistic approach to be displayed while the lead character rewinds time.<ref name="obstacles">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/watch-life-is-strange-dev-talks-time-travel-butter/1100-6424849/ |title=Watch: Life is Strange Dev Talks Time-Travel Butterfly Effect in New Video |first=Eddie |last=Makuch |date=23 January 2015 |work=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=24 January 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150125111127/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/watch-life-is-strange-dev-talks-time-travel-butter/1100-6424849/ |archivedate=25 January 2015  }}</ref> The textures seen in the game were entirely hand painted, adapted to achieve what art director Michel Koch called "impressionistic rendering".<ref name="rendering">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamereactor.eu/previews/249994/Life+is+Strange/ |title=One of the oddest reveals of Gamescom also proved to be one of the most interesting. Here's what the Remember Me developers did next. |first=Christian |last=Gaca |date=22 August 2014 |work=[[Gamereactor]] |accessdate=11 November 2014 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141221190043/http://www.gamereactor.eu/previews/249994/Life%2Bis%2BStrange/ |archivedate=21 December 2014  }}</ref> Elements were adjusted based on player feedback,<ref name="birth" /> with influences like ''[[The Walking Dead (video game)|The Walking Dead]]'', ''[[Gone Home]]''{{ref|1|1}} and ''[[Heavy Rain]]'' in mind.<ref name="analogue" /><ref name="influences">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/manifesto/juno--donnie-darko--gone-home--life-is-strange-30843#/slide/8|title=Juno + Donnie Darko + Gone Home = Life is Strange|first=Blake|last=Peterson|date=26 January 2015|work=[[Game Revolution]]|accessdate=29 January 2015|archivedate=29 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150129222908/http://www.gamerevolution.com/manifesto/juno--donnie-darko--gone-home--life-is-strange-30843#/slide/8|deadurl=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''[[The Catcher in the Rye]]'' was an additional source of inspiration, whose protagonist [[Holden Caulfield]] shares a surname with Max, the game's lead.<ref name="catcher">{{cite web|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2015/02/05/life-strange-director-talks-theme-identity-visual-novels/|title=Life Is Strange Director Talks About The Theme Of "Identity" And Visual Novels|date=5 February 2015|work=Siliconera|accessdate=6 February 2015|archivedate=10 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150210122205/http://www.siliconera.com/2015/02/05/life-strange-director-talks-theme-identity-visual-novels/|deadurl=no}}</ref> The characters were created using known [[archetype]]s, at first to establish an entry point for the player, and then to subvert them.<ref name="archetypes">{{cite web|url=http://www.idigitaltimes.com/life-strange-episode-2-dev-talks-us-about-whats-next-max-arcadia-bay-exclusive-424890 |title='Life is Strange Episode 2' Dev Talks To Us About What's Next For Max In Arcadia Bay [EXCLUSIVE] |first=Zulai |last=Serrano |date=23 March 2015 |work=[[IBT Media#Assets|iDigitalTimes]] |accessdate=25 March 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324104026/http://www.idigitaltimes.com/life-strange-episode-2-dev-talks-us-about-whats-next-max-arcadia-bay-exclusive-424890 |archivedate=24 March 2015  }}</ref> For the sake of serving the [[Realism (arts)|realism]], the supernatural elements were designed as a metaphor for the characters' inner conflict,<ref name="innerconflict">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamereactor.eu/news/288154/Life+is+Strange+-+%22Supernatural+things+merely+metaphors%22/ |title=Life is Strange – "Supernatural things merely metaphors" |first=Bengt |last=Lemne |date=26 January 2015 |work=[[Gamereactor]] |accessdate=26 January 2015 |archivedate= 6 February 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206225023/http://www.gamereactor.eu/news/288154/Life%2Bis%2BStrange%2B-%2B%22Supernatural%2Bthings%2Bmerely%2Bmetaphors%22/ |deadurl=no  }}</ref> and experts were consulted to tackle the subject of [[Youth suicide|teen suicide]].<ref name="experts">{{cite web|url=http://www.polygon.com/2016/3/15/11226888/life-is-strange-gdc-2016 |title=How Life is Strange just might save lives — in-game and in real life |first=Allegra |last=Frank |date=15 March 2016 |work=[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] |accessdate=24 March 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160318134333/http://www.polygon.com/2016/3/15/11226888/life-is-strange-gdc-2016 |archivedate=18 March 2016  }}</ref>

The score was composed by Jonathan Morali of the band [[Syd Matters]].<ref name="perspective">{{cite web|url=http://www.vg247.com/2015/01/29/life-is-strange-pc-ps4-xbox-one-video/|title=Life is Strange launch trailer and final dev diary released|first=Stephany|last=Nunneley|date=29 January 2015|work=[[VG247]]|accessdate=21 July 2015|archivedate=29 January 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150129233119/http://www.vg247.com/2015/01/29/life-is-strange-pc-ps4-xbox-one-video/|deadurl=no}}</ref> Inspired by modern [[indie folk]] music,<ref name="50%" /><ref name="highlighting" /> the soundtrack was intended to inform the mood of the game.<ref name="repercussion" /> The music contains a blend of licensed tracks and composed pieces.<ref name="50%">{{cite web|url=http://www.dualshockers.com/2014/10/09/life-is-strange-creative-director-jean-maxime-moris-talks-atmosphere-choices-and-female-leads/|title=Life Is Strange Creative Director Jean-Maxime Moris Talks Atmosphere, Choices, and Female Leads|first=Joel|last=Taveras|date=9 October 2014|work=DualShockers|accessdate=11 November 2014|archivedate=12 November 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141112040959/http://www.dualshockers.com/2014/10/09/life-is-strange-creative-director-jean-maxime-moris-talks-atmosphere-choices-and-female-leads/|deadurl=no}}</ref> Featured artists include [[José González (singer)|José González]], [[Mogwai]], [[Breton (band)|Breton]], [[Amanda Palmer]], [[Brian Viglione]], [[Bright Eyes (band)|Bright Eyes]], Message to Bears, [[Local Natives]], Syd Matters, [[Sparklehorse]], [[Angus & Julia Stone]], [[alt-J]], Mud Flow<ref name="artists">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamespot.com/articles/these-are-the-songs-in-life-is-strange/1100-6425751/ |title=These Are the Songs in Life is Strange |first=Alexa Ray |last=Corriea |date=7 March 2015 |work=[[GameSpot]] |accessdate=7 March 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150309211114/http://www.gamespot.com/articles/these-are-the-songs-in-life-is-strange/1100-6425751/ |archivedate=9 March 2015  }}</ref> and [[Foals (band)|Foals]].<ref name="NAEU" />

==Release==
Square Enix and Dontnod announced ''Life Is Strange'' on 11 August 2014.<ref name="direct">{{cite web|url=http://eu.square-enix.com/en/blog/announcing-life-strange|title=Announcing Life is Strange!|first=Toby|last=Palm|date=11 August 2014|work=[[Square Enix]]|accessdate=10 December 2014|archivedate=21 October 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021194250/http://eu.square-enix.com/en/blog/announcing-life-strange|deadurl=no}}</ref> The episodes were released digitally on [[Microsoft Windows|PC]] via [[Steam (software)|Steam]], [[PlayStation 3]] and [[PlayStation 4]] via [[PlayStation Network]], and [[Xbox 360]] and [[Xbox One]] via [[Xbox Live]] between 30 January 2015 and 20 October 2015.<ref name="30 January 2015">{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/12/17/life-is-strange-gets-a-release-date-and-pricing-info|title=Life is Strange Gets a Release Date and Pricing Info|first=Wesley|last=Copeland|date=17 December 2014|work=[[IGN]]|accessdate=17 December 2014|archivedate=17 February 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150217003020/http://www.ign.com/articles/2014/12/17/life-is-strange-gets-a-release-date-and-pricing-info|deadurl=no}}</ref><ref name="20 October 2015">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezone.com/news/life-is-strange-episode-5-release-date-revealed-in-new-trailer-3426071 |title=Life is Strange Episode 5 release date revealed in new trailer |first=Mike |last=Boccher |date=7 October 2015 |work=GameZone |accessdate=12 October 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151010095519/http://www.gamezone.com/news/life-is-strange-episode-5-release-date-revealed-in-new-trailer-3426071 |archivedate=10 October 2015  }}</ref> In November 2014, the publisher said they were interested in releasing [[Video game packaging|physical copies]] of the game, but said that at that time they were "100 per cent focused on the digital release".<ref name="per cent">{{cite web|url=http://www.videogamer.com/ps4/life_is_strange/news/square_enix_considering_boxed_release_for_life_is_strange.html|title=Square Enix considering boxed release for Life is Strange|first=David|last=Scammell|date=19 November 2014|work=VideoGamer.com|accessdate=6 December 2014|archivedate=8 December 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141208080118/http://www.videogamer.com/ps4/life_is_strange/news/square_enix_considering_boxed_release_for_life_is_strange.html|deadurl=no}}</ref> One year later, the retail edition was set to be released for the PC, PS4 and Xbox One in North America on 19 January 2016 and in Europe on 22 January 2016; the [[Special edition|limited edition]] had an artbook, the soundtrack, score, and a director's commentary.<ref name="NAEU">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/11/23/life-is-strange-limited-edition-coming-to-north-america-for-pc/178900/ |title=Life Is Strange Limited Edition Coming to North America for PC |first=Adnan |last=Riaz |date=23 November 2015 |work=[[Hardcore Gamer]] |accessdate=23 November 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151124115414/http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/11/23/life-is-strange-limited-edition-coming-to-north-america-for-pc/178900/ |archivedate=24 November 2015  }}</ref><ref name="score">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/11/12/life-is-strange-limited-edition-announced/176838/ |title=Life is Strange Limited Edition Announced |first=Adam |last=Beck |date=12 November 2015 |work=[[Hardcore Gamer]] |accessdate=12 November 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151115010710/http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/11/12/life-is-strange-limited-edition-announced/176838/ |archivedate=15 November 2015  }}</ref> A Japanese version was released for Microsoft Windows, PlayStation 3 and PlayStation 4 on 3 March 2016.<ref name="japanese">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/12/10/life-is-stranges-japanese-version-receives-a-release-date/181870/ |title=Life Is Strange’s Japanese Version Receives a Release Date |first=Adnan |last=Riaz |date=10 December 2015 |work=[[Hardcore Gamer]] |accessdate=10 December 2015 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151211050238/http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2015/12/10/life-is-stranges-japanese-version-receives-a-release-date/181870/ |archivedate=11 December 2015  }}</ref> [[Feral Interactive]] ported ''Life Is Strange'' for [[OS X]], released on 16 June 2016,<ref name="mac">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/275134/Life_is_Strange_ndash_out_now_on_the_Mac_App_Store_Thecritically_acclaimed_Life_is_Strangetrade_is_now_available_on_theMac_App_Store_Life_is_Strange_is_a_unique_fivepart_adventure_thatexplores_complex_issues_with_an_innovative_take_on_storybased.php |title=Life is Strange – out now on the Mac App Store The critically acclaimed Life is Strange is now available on the Mac App Store! Life is Strange is a unique five-part adventure that explores complex issues with an innovative take on story-based |date=16 June 2016 |work=[[Gamasutra]] |accessdate=16 June 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160922213029/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/275134/Life_is_Strange_ndash_out_now_on_the_Mac_App_Store_Thecritically_acclaimed_Life_is_Strangetrade_is_now_available_on_theMac_App_Store_Life_is_Strange_is_a_unique_fivepart_adventure_thatexplores_complex_issues_with_an_innovative_take_on_storybased.php |archivedate=22 September 2016  }}</ref> and [[Linux]],<ref name="porting">{{cite web|url=http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2016/06/01/feral-interactive-confirms-life-is-strange-is-coming-to-mac-linux/209664/ |title=Feral Interactive Confirms Life Is Strange is Coming to Mac, Linux |first=Adnan |last=Riaz |date=1 June 2016 |work=[[Hardcore Gamer]] |accessdate=2 June 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160602111105/http://www.hardcoregamer.com/2016/06/01/feral-interactive-confirms-life-is-strange-is-coming-to-mac-linux/209664/ |archivedate=2 June 2016  }}</ref> released on 21 July 2016.<ref name="linux">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/277641/Life_Is_Strange_is_out_now_on_Steam_for_Mac_and_Linux_withthe_first_episode_available_for_free.php |title=Life Is Strange is out now on Steam for Mac and Linux, with the first episode available for free! |date=21 July 2016 |work=[[Gamasutra]] |accessdate=22 July 2016 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160725161020/http://www.gamasutra.com/view/pressreleases/277641/Life_Is_Strange_is_out_now_on_Steam_for_Mac_and_Linux_withthe_first_episode_available_for_free.php |archivedate=25 July 2016  }}</ref> That same day, the first episode was made indefinitely available for free on Linux,<ref name="linux" /> Windows, OS X, PS3, PS4, Xbox 360 and Xbox One.<ref name="indefinitely">{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/691827/Life-is-Strange-free-download-PS4-PS3-PlayStation-Plus-Xbox-One-Xbox-360-PC-Mac|title=Life is Strange free download confirmed for PS4 and PS3, regardless of PlayStation Plus|first=Liam|last=Martin|date=21 July 2016|work=[[Daily Express]]|accessdate=21 July 2016|archivedate=29 July 2016|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20160729212438/http://www.express.co.uk/entertainment/gaming/691827/Life-is-Strange-free-download-PS4-PS3-PlayStation-Plus-Xbox-One-Xbox-360-PC-Mac|deadurl=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> ''Life Is Strange'' was included on [[PlayStation Plus]] for the month of June 2017.<ref name="strange killing">{{cite web|url=https://blog.eu.playstation.com/2017/05/31/killing-floor-2-and-life-is-strange-are-your-playstation-plus-games-for-june/|title=Killing Floor 2 and Life is Strange are your PlayStation Plus games for June|first=Matthew|last=Groizard|date=31 May 2017|website=[[PlayStation Blog]]|publisher=[[Sony Interactive Entertainment]]|archivedate=31 May 2017|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170531172816/https://blog.eu.playstation.com/2017/05/31/killing-floor-2-and-life-is-strange-are-your-playstation-plus-games-for-june/|deadurl=no|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It was released for [[iOS]] on 14 December 2017, and launched on [[Android (operating system)|Android]] in July 2018, both ported by [[Black Wing Foundation]].<ref name="GamesBeat-Dec2017">{{cite web|url=https://venturebeat.com/2017/12/12/life-is-strange-will-launch-for-ios-on-december-14/|title=Life is Strange will launch for iOS on December 14|first=Mike|last=Minotti|date=12 December 2017|website=[[GamesBeat]]}}</ref><ref name="Engadget-Dec2017">{{cite web|url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/12/12/life-is-strange-iphone-ipad-december-14th/|title='Life is Strange' comes to iPhone and iPad December 14th|first=Rob|last=LeFebvre|date=12 December 2017|website=[[Engadget]]}}</ref><ref name="Riaz-Jun2018">{{cite web|url=https://www.hardcoregamer.com/2018/06/04/life-is-strange-arrives-next-month-for-android-exclusive-controller-support-confirmed/301109/|title=Life Is Strange Arrives Next Month for Android, Exclusive Controller Support Confirmed|first=Adnan|last=Riaz|date=4 June 2018|website=[[Hardcore Gamer]]|archivedate=4 June 2018|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20180604155316/https://www.hardcoregamer.com/2018/06/04/life-is-strange-arrives-next-month-for-android-exclusive-controller-support-confirmed/301109/|deadurl=no|access-date=4 June 2018|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

